{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20181016021515|864251633","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Elizabeth_Esty","to":"Elizabeth Esty"}],"pages":{"36733622":{"pageid":36733622,"ns":0,"title":"Elizabeth Esty","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-20T19:10:32Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Elizabeth Esty\n|image        = Elizabeth Esty 114th official portrait.jpg\n|state        = [[Connecticut]]\n|district     = {{ushr|CT|5|5th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2013\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Chris Murphy]]\n|successor    = \n|state_house1 = Connecticut\n|district1    = 103rd\n|term_start1  = January 7, 2009\n|term_end1    = January 5, 2011\n|predecessor1 = [[Al Adinolfi]]\n|successor1   = Al Adinolfi <!-- Don't add link per MOS:OVERLINK. -->\n|birth_name   = Elizabeth Henderson\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1959|8|25}}\n|birth_place  = [[Oak Park, Illinois]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = [[Daniel C. Esty|Daniel Esty]]\n|children     = 3<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elizabethesty.com/about/|title=Meet Elizabeth|website=Elizabeth Esty for U.S. Congress|publisher=Friends of Elizabeth Esty}}</ref>\n|education    = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Yale University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website      = {{url|esty.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Esty''' (n\u00e9e Henderson; born August 25, 1959) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from {{ushr|CT|5}}, elected in 2012. She is a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]. Previously she was a member of the [[Connecticut House of Representatives]], representing the 103rd Assembly District, which consisted of [[Cheshire, Connecticut|Cheshire]] and parts of [[Hamden, Connecticut|Hamden]] and [[Wallingford, Connecticut|Wallingford]]. She also served two terms on the Cheshire Town Council. The 5th congressional district spans central and northwest Connecticut, including Waterbury, Danbury, New Britain, Meriden, Torrington, Litchfield County, the Farmington Valley, Newtown, and Esty's hometown of Cheshire.\n\nEsty defeated two challengers in the August 14, 2012, Democratic primary to become the Democratic nominee in [[Connecticut's 5th congressional district]], and on November 6, 2012, she defeated challenger [[Andrew Roraback]]. Esty defeated Mark Greenberg on November 4, 2014, in the state's most competitive district to win her first re-election.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Esty beats Greenberg in Key 5th District|url=http://ctmirror.org/2014/11/04/esty-beats-greenberg-in-5th-district|newspaper=[[The Connecticut Mirror]]|accessdate =November 7, 2015|first=Arielle|last=Levin Becker|first2=Melissa|last2=Collins|date=November 4, 2014}}</ref> On November 8, 2016, Esty defeated Sherman First Selectman Clay Cope by a margin of 58%\u201342% to win re-election a second time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/election/results/states/connecticut/house/05|title=Full 2016 election results: Connecticut House 05|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=February 24, 2017|date=2016}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2018, Esty faced public criticism after news reports revealed that her former chief of staff had been accused of sexual harassment and threats of violence against staff but that she kept him on the payroll for another three months and wrote him a positive letter of reference.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/02/us/politics/elizabeth-esty-wont-run-reelection.html|title=Elizabeth Esty, Saying She Mishandled Abuse Claim, Won\u2019t Defend House Seat|first=Liam|last=Stack|date=April 2, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> After initially insisting she would continue to serve, Esty announced that she would not seek reelection.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/30/politics/elizabeth-esty-staffer-abuse/index.html|title=Congresswoman who kept on top aide after learning of abuse allegations not resigning|first1=Veronica|last1=Stracqualursi|first2=MJ|last2=Lee|work=[[CNN]]|date=March 30, 2018|access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/02/politics/elizabeth-esty-resign/index.html|title=Elizabeth Esty just bowed to the inevitable|first=Chris|last=Cillizza|work=CNN|date=April 2, 2018|access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> She cited her failure to protect women on her staff from sexual harassment and threats of violence from her former chief of staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aol.com/article/news/2018/04/02/connecticut-rep-elizabeth-esty-not-seeking-re-election-to-us-house/23401226/|title=Connecticut Rep. Elizabeth Esty not seeking re-election|work=[[AOL]]|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=April 2, 2018|first1=Amanda|last1=Becker|first2=Richard|last2=Cowan}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and career==\nElizabeth Henderson was born in 1959 in [[Oak Park, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Elizabeth Esty, D (Conn.-5)|url=http://www.rollcall.com/new-members/elizabeth-esty-house-d-conn-5.html|work=[[Roll Call]]|issue=Roll Call New Member Profiles: 113th Congress|date=November 7, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304071732/http://www.rollcall.com/new-members/elizabeth-esty-house-d-conn-5.html|archivedate=March 4, 2016}}</ref> Her father worked as an engineer in a construction company and the family moved numerous times during her childhood. She was raised in [[Minnesota]] and graduated from [[Winona Senior High School]]. She earned an B.A. from [[Harvard College]] in 1981 and a J.D. from [[Yale Law School]] in 1985. She also studied International Relations at L'Institut d'\u00e9tudes politiques in Paris for a year on a [[Ambassadorial Scholarships|Rotary Ambassadorial Scholarship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ct5thdistrict.registercitizen.com/elizabeth-esty/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419024024/http://ct5thdistrict.registercitizen.com/elizabeth-esty/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=April 19, 2012|title=Redlands Daily Facts Blogs|publisher=|df=mdy-all}}<!-- redirects to http://blogs.redlandsdailyfacts.com/, an empty blog site --></ref> Esty volunteered for [[Planned Parenthood]] in college.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ct5thdistrict.registercitizen.com/elizabeth-esty/4/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022022428/http://ct5thdistrict.registercitizen.com/elizabeth-esty/4/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2013-10-22|title=Redlands Daily Facts Blogs|publisher=}}<!-- redirects to http://blogs.redlandsdailyfacts.com/, an empty blog site --></ref>\n\nEsty has been a law clerk for a federal judge, a Supreme Court lawyer at [[Sidley Austin LLP]] in Washington, D.C., and professor at [[American University]]. She is a member of the Cheshire Public Library Board, Legal Advisor to the [[League of Women Voters|Connecticut League of Women Voters Consensus Project]], chair of the Board of Trustees for the First Congregational Church of Cheshire, lay member of the Committee on Ministry New Haven Association of the [[United Church of Christ]], and a member of the Parent-Teacher Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/72826|title=Elizabeth Esty's Biography |work=Project Vote Smart}}</ref>\n\n==Connecticut House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 2008, she challenged Republican State Representative [[Al Adinolfi]] of Connecticut's 103rd Assembly District. She defeated him 51%-49%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=455786|title=CT State House 103 Race - Nov 04, 2008 |publisher=Our Campaigns}}</ref> In 2010, Adinolfi challenged her in a rematch and defeated her 51%\u201349%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=664825|title=CT State House 103 Race - Nov 02, 2010|publisher=Our Campaigns}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nShe opposed Governor [[Jodi Rell]]'s proposal to eliminate the state's Office of Consumer Counsel. She cut her own pay by 10%. When [[aerospace]] manufacturer [[Pratt & Whitney]] closed its Cheshire plant in 2009, Esty was among several politicians who fought to get workers new job placements or early retirement packages. She opposes the [[Capital punishment in Connecticut|death penalty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ct5thdistrict.registercitizen.com/elizabeth-esty/8/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022002320/http://ct5thdistrict.registercitizen.com/elizabeth-esty/8/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2013-10-22|title=Redlands Daily Facts Blogs|publisher=}}<!-- redirects to http://blogs.redlandsdailyfacts.com/, an empty blog site --></ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*Appropriations Committee\n*Energy and Technology Committee\n*Public Health Committee<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ballotpedia.org/wiki/index.php/Elizabeth_Esty|title=Elizabeth Esty|publisher=ballotpedia}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2012 election===\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Connecticut, 2012#District 5}}\nIn 2012, Democratic U.S. Congressman [[Chris Murphy (Connecticut politician)|Chris Murphy]] of [[Connecticut's 5th congressional district]] decided to retire in order to run for the U.S. Senate. Esty decided to run. She was endorsed by [[EMILY's List]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://atr.rollcall.com/connecticut-elizabeth-esty-wins-5th-district-democratic-nomination/|title=Connecticut: Elizabeth Esty Wins 5th District Democratic Nomination|author=AbLivingston|date=August 15, 2012|work=Roll Call}}</ref> She also won the newspaper endorsements from ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[Hartford Courant]]'' and the ''[[Torrington, Connecticut|Torrington]] Register-Citizen''. She defeated Daniel Roberti and State House Speaker [[Christopher G. Donovan|Chris Donovan]] in the primary.\n\nIn the November 6 [[general election]], Esty defeated State Senator [[Andrew Roraback]] to become the district's next representative.<ref>{{cite news |last=Christoffersen|first=John|title=Democrat Esty wins Conn.'s 5th District seat|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Democrat-Esty-wins-Conn-s-5th-District-seat-4015182.php|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate=November 8, 2012}}</ref> Esty won despite the opposition of New York Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]], whose PAC channeled over a million dollars to her opponent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://politicker.com/2012/11/bloombergs-super-pac-narrowly-misses-most-congressional-targets/ |title=Bloomberg's Super PAC Narrowly Misses Most Congressional Targets |author=Colin Campbell |date=November 7, 2012|work=Observer}}</ref>\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title = Connecticut 5th Congressional District 2012<ref name=ConnSS>{{cite web|url=http://www.sots.ct.gov/sots/lib/sots/electionservices/electionresults/2012/2012_election_results.pdf|title=Secretary of the State Denise W. Merrill|publisher=}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = '''Elizabeth Esty'''\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = '''142,201'''<ref>Includes 8,609 votes received on the line of the [[Connecticut Working Families Party]], which [[fusion voting|cross-endorsed]]</ref>\n| percentage = '''51.62%'''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Andrew Roraback\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 133,256<ref>Includes 9,710 votes as listed as an Independent on the ballot.</ref>\n| percentage = 48.37%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change\n| candidate = John Pistone\n| party = Write-In\n| votes = 12\n| percentage = 0.00\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change\n| candidate = Russ Jaeger\n| party = Write-In\n| votes = 10\n| percentage = 0.00\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 284,757\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n=== 2014 election ===\nIn 2014, Esty defeated her Republican opponent, Mark Greenberg, earning 53.2% of the vote to Greenberg's 45.8%, despite Greenberg spending more than $1,600,000 of his own money on the campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fec.gov/fecviewer/CandidateCommitteeDetail.do|title=Committee/Candidate Search|publisher=FEC |accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |'''U.S. House, Connecticut District 5 General Election, 2014'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |Party\n|Candidate\n|Vote %\n|Votes\n|-\n|\n|Democratic\n|'''Elizabeth Esty''' '''''Incumbent'''''\n|53.2%\n|113,564\n|-\n|\n|Republican\n|Mark Greenberg\n|45.8%\n|97,767\n|-\n|\n|Independent\n|John Pistone\n|0.9%\n|1,970\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" |'''Total Votes'''\n|'''213,301'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |''Source:'' Connecticut Secretary of the State\n|}\n\n=== 2016 election ===\nIn 2016, Esty defeated Republican Clay Cope, the First Selectman of [[Sherman, Connecticut]], earning 58% of the vote to Cope's 42%. Esty won 27 of the district's 41 cities and towns \u2013 including seven in which [[Donald Trump]] outperformed [[Hillary Clinton]]. Esty won Cope's hometown of Sherman.\n\nEsty received the endorsements of the ''[[Hartford Courant]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/opinion/editorials/hc-ed-elizabeth-esty-reelect-to-congress-20141023-story.html|title=Esty Has Earned Re-Election In 5th District|author=Editorial |newspaper=Hartford Courant |accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Republican-American|Waterbury Republican-American]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rep-am.com/opinion/editorials/2016/11/03/we-endorse-9/|title=We endorse|date=November 3, 2016 |newspaper=Republican-American|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The News-Times|Danbury News-Times]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newstimes.com/news/article/Endorsement-Esty-deserves-a-third-term-10421975.php|title=Endorsement: Esty deserves a third term|newspaper=NewsTimes|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Record-Journal|Meriden Record-Journal]]'',<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.myrecordjournal.com/news/latestnews/9550611-154/editorial-r-j-endorsement-for-congress-us-senate.html|title=Editorial: R-J endorsement for Congress, U.S. Senate |newspaper=[[Record-Journal]] |accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> ''[[New Haven Register]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nhregister.com/opinion/20161105/the-new-haven-register-endorses-entire-slate-of-incumbent-congressional-delegates|title=The New Haven Register endorses entire slate of incumbent Congressional delegates|accessdate=February 24, 2017 }}</ref> ''Newtown Bee'',<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://newtownbee.com/election-day-choices-color-the-future/|title=Election Day Choices Color The Future |newspaper=Newtown Bee |accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> and ''Lakeville Journal''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.tricornernews.com/node/48498|title=Our endorsements |newspaper=Lakeville Journal |accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |'''U.S. House, Connecticut District 5 General Election, 2016'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |Party\n|Candidate\n|Vote %\n|Votes\n|-\n|\n|Democratic\n|'''Elizabeth Esty''' '''''Incumbent'''''\n|58%\n|179,252\n|-\n|\n|Republican\n|Clay Cope\n|42%\n|129,801\n|-\n|\n|N/A\n|Write-in\n|0%\n|29\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" |'''Total Votes'''\n|'''309,082'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |''Source: Connecticut Secretary of State''\n|}\n\n=== 2018 election ===\nEsty announced on the April 2, 2018 that she will not be seeking reelection in the upcoming 2018 midterm election. This news comes after a scandal involving her chief of staff, Tony Baker, and accusers of sexual harassment. Esty neglected to follow up on these charges with any discipline for a considerable time as well as approving a $5,000 severance package as well as providing Baker with a letter of recommendation from Esty herself to garner a position on the Sandy Hook Promise Council.Republicans and Democrats, local newspapers and bi-partisan citizens called for her resignation.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n=== Tenure ===\nEsty introduced the Collinsville Renewable Energy Promotion Act in February 2013 allow the town of [[Canton, Connecticut]], to take over two lapsed licenses from the [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission|Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC)]] in order to refurbish two old local dams.<ref>{{cite news|title=Elizabeth Esty's first bill, reintroduced Collinsville dams legislation, passes House|url=http://www.foothillsmediagroup.com/articles/2013/02/18/canton/news/doc51228c29d578e656011125.txt|accessdate=April 12, 2013|newspaper=The Avon News|date=February 18, 2013}}</ref> The dams would be used to produce [[Hydroelectricity|hydroelectric power]].<ref name=316sum>{{cite web|title=H.R 316 - 113th Congress|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/316|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=April 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Esty voted against repeal of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]]. She then subsequently voted to delay the individual and business mandates in the law by one year.;<ref>{{cite news |title=Esty Statement on Bills to Delay ACA Penalties for One Year |url=http://www.stamfordplus.com/stm/information/nws1/publish/News_1/Esty-Statement-on-Bills-to-Delay-ACA-Penalties-for-One-Year20533.shtml |publisher=StamfordPlus.com |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nEsty co-authored<ref>{{Cite web |title=Esty bill on tech education passes House |url = http://blog.ctnews.com/politics/2015/02/25/esty-bill-on-tech-education-passes-house/ |publisher=CT Politics |accessdate=November 7, 2015}}</ref> the [[STEM Education Act of 2014 (H.R. 5031; 113th Congress)|STEM Education Act (H.R. 5031; 113th Congress)]] [https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/1020?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22stem+education%22%5D%7D&resultIndex=1 (H.R. 1020; 114th Congress)]. This bill strengthens science, technology, engineering and math (STEM) education efforts and expands the definition of STEM to include computer science.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Smith\u2019s STEM Education Act Signed Into Law|url = https://science.house.gov/news/press-releases/smith-s-stem-education-act-signed-law|website = Committee on Science, Space, and Technology |accessdate =November 7, 2015}}</ref> She said that \"STEM education is critical to preparing our students for high-demand careers in [[engineering]], [[manufacturing]], and [[information technology]].\"<ref name=Callahan1>{{cite news |last1=Callahan |first1=Molly |title=House passes Rep. Esty's STEM Education Act|url=http://www.myrecordjournal.com/meriden/meridennews/5036761-129/house-passes-rep-estys-stem-education-act.html |accessdate=July 16, 2014 |publisher=My Record Journal|date=July 15, 2014}}</ref> According to Esty, she frequently hears from \"manufactures and small business owners that it's increasingly difficult to find workers with the right skill sets to fill the jobs in demand.\" The House easily approved this bill with a vote of 412-8<ref>{{Cite news |title = Esty wins on STEM bill |url=http://ctmirror.org/2015/02/25/esty-wins-on-stem-bill/ |newspaper = [[The Connecticut Mirror]] |accessdate=November 7, 2015 |first=Ana |last=Radelat}}</ref> and it was signed into law in October 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Plainville High STEM best in state, Esty says |url=http://www.centralctcommunications.com/bristolpress/article_ae0498f4-7c4d-11e5-8cad-03fc987153c3.html|publisher = Central Connecticut Communications |accessdate=November 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nEsty also authored the Gold Star Fathers Act. This bill extends formal hiring preference for federal jobs to fathers of disabled and deceased veterans.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://esty.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/estys-gold-star-fathers-act-signed-law|title=Esty's Gold Star Fathers Act Signed Into Law |date=October 8, 2015 |publisher=Congresswoman Elizabeth Esty|accessdate=February 24, 2017 }}</ref> (Previously, only Gold Star mothers were eligible for hiring preference.) [[Ron Wyden|Senator Ron Wyden (D-OR)]] introduced companion legislation in the [[U.S. Senate]]. The bill passed both chambers of Congress, and it was signed into law by [[Barack Obama]] on October 8, 2015.\n\nThrough her role on the Committee and Transportation and Infrastructure, Esty helped craft the [[Fixing America\u2019s Surface Transportation Act]], which was passed by Congress on December 3, 2015, and signed into law by then-President Obama on December 4, 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/finance/262049-senate-sends-highway-bill-to-obama|title=Senate sends $305B highway bill to Obama|last=Goad|first=Ben|date=December 3, 2015 |newspaper=The Hill|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> Esty sponsored an amendment to ease weight limits on the weight of trucks transporting dairy products, which reduces the number of trucks needed to transport milk. That amendment was included in the final legislation. Esty also sponsored amendments to increase Buy America requirements for buses and rail cars, establish new National Electric Vehicle Charging, Hydrogen, Propane, and Natural Gas Fueling Corridors, and protect pollinator habitat and forage on transportation rights-of-way.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://esty.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/esty-applauds-house-passage-long-term-transportation-legislation-fix|title=Esty Applauds House Passage of Long-Term Transportation Legislation to Fix Roads, Bridges, Transit Systems|date=December 3, 2015 |publisher=Congresswoman Elizabeth Esty|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nEsty has sponsored multiple pieces of legislation designed to help cities and towns combat the opioid addiction epidemic. On March 3, 2016, she introduced the Prevent Drug Addiction Act, which calls for new consumer education campaigns on the risks of opioid addiction, strengthen training requirements for medical practitioners eligible to prescribe opioids or participate in opioid treatment programs, require opioid treatment programs to make acceptable arrangements for patients to receive needed medications on days when the program is closed for business to reduce the risk of relapse for patients in recovery, and create a new drug management program under the Medicare Part D Prescription Drug Plan to prevent high-risk Medicare beneficiaries from becoming addicted to prescription drugs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/4697?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22prevent+drug+addiction+act%22%5D%7D&r=2|title=Prevent Drug Addiction Act |publisher=Congress.gov }}</ref> In May 2016, Esty served on the conference committee charged with crafting legislation to combat opioid addiction.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://esty.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/esty-courtney-serve-conference-committee-negotiate-opioid-addiction-bill|title=Esty, Courtney to Serve on Conference Committee to Negotiate Opioid Addiction Bill|date=May 17, 2016 |publisher=Congresswoman Elizabeth Esty|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> Portions of Esty's Prevent Drug Addiction Act were included in the bill, including the pain management program for Medicare Part D beneficiaries. The final legislation, the [[Comprehensive Addiction and Recovery Act]], was signed into law on July 22, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/senate-bill/524|title=Comprehensive Addiction and Recovery Act |publisher=Congress.gov }}</ref>\n\nConnecticut's Fifth District includes [[Newtown, Connecticut]], which was the site of the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting|mass shooting]] at [[Sandy Hook Elementary School]] on December 14, 2012. Esty serves as a vice-chair of the House Gun Violence Prevention Task Force. She is an original cosponsor of the Public Safety and Second Amendment Rights Protection Act, which would require background checks on all commercial firearm sales.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/1217|title=ublic Safety and Second Amendment Rights Protection Act |publisher=Congress.gov}}</ref> On May 29, 2014, Esty and a bipartisan group of House lawmakers introduced an amendment to increase funding to the [[National Instant Criminal Background Check System]]. The amendment passed the House by a vote of 260-145.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://time.com/136967/house-passes-bill-to-boost-funding-for-gun-background-checks/|title=House Passes Bill to Boost Funding for Gun Background Checks|work=Time|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> On June 22, 2016, Esty and several Democrats held a 26-hour sit-in on the floor of the House of Representatives to protest Speaker of the House [[Paul Ryan]]'s refusal to allow the House to vote on legislation related to gun violence prevention.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-house-democrats-sit-in-gun-vote-20160622-snap-htmlstory.html|title='No bill, no break': House Democrats continue sit-in protest into early morning|last=Mascaro|first=Lisa|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=February 24, 2017 |last2=Wire|first2=Sarah D. |issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Esty's office, Esty reclaimed more than $10,000,000 in government benefits \u2013 including overdue veterans' benefits, [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] payments, [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] payments, and delayed tax refunds \u2013 for residents of Connecticut's Fifth District through her first two terms in office.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://esty.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/esty-recovers-10000000th-dollar-savings-and-benefits-connecticut|title=Esty Recovers 10,000,000th Dollar in Savings and Benefits for Connecticut Families|date=November 1, 2016 |publisher=Congresswoman Elizabeth Esty|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nEsty was ranked as the 62nd most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives during the [[114th United States Congress]] (and the most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives from Connecticut) in the Bipartisan Index created by [[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]] and the [[McCourt School of Public Policy]] that ranks members of the United States Congress by their degree of bipartisanship (by measuring the frequency each member's bills attract co-sponsors from the opposite party and each member's co-sponsorship of bills by members of the opposite party).<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20House%20Scores.pdf|title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index|publisher=[[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]]|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the 115th Congress convened in January 2017, Esty was named the Vice Ranking Member of the Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.centralctcommunications.com/newbritainherald/article_66c34170-e376-11e6-8187-077fc32d57a4.html|title=Esty elected ranking member in House committee|publisher=Central Connecticut Communications|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> She was also elected to the Veterans' Affairs Committee, where she now serves as Ranking Member of the Subcommittee on Disability Assistance and Memorial Affairs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://esty.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/esty-named-top-democrat-subcommittee-overseeing-veterans-benefits|title=Esty Named Top Democrat on Subcommittee Overseeing Veterans' Benefits|date=February 15, 2017|publisher=Congresswoman Elizabeth Esty|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn partnership with Republican Rep. [[Barbara Comstock]] of [[Virginia]], Esty introduced the Promoting Women in Entrepreneurship Act and the INSPIRE Women Act, a pair of bills designed to improve federal support for women in science, technology, math, and engineering fields. Both bills passed the House and Senate by unanimous consent and are pending signature by President [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.inc.com/elizabeth-gore/what-could-trump-sign-worth-30b-a-bill-for-women-entrepreneurs.html|title=Why Trump Needs to Sign New Bills For Women Entrepreneurs|date=February 22, 2017 |publisher=Inc.com|accessdate=February 24, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n**[https://science.house.gov/subcommittees/subcommittee-research-and-technology-114th-congress Subcommittee on Research and Technology]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]] (Vice Ranking Member)'''\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n**[http://transportation.house.gov/subcommittees/subcommittee/?ID=107422 Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]\n*[[United States House Committee on Veterans' Affairs|'''Committee on Veterans' Affairs''']]\n**[[United States House Veterans' Affairs Subcommittee on Disability Assistance and Memorial Affairs|Subcommittee on Disability Assistance and Memorial Affairs]] (Ranking Member)\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*'''[[New Democrat Coalition]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://newdemocratcoalition-himes.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=New Democrat Coalition|date=|accessdate=6 February 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Congressional Arts Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Climate Solutions Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=90 Current Climate Solutions Caucus Members|author=|url=https://citizensclimatelobby.org/climate-solutions-caucus/|format=| publisher=Citizen\u00b4s Climate Lobby |date=|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nElizabeth Henderson married [[Daniel C. Esty]] in 1984. Several years later, their first child, Sarah, was born while they were working in [[Washington, D.C.]] Elizabeth became a stay-at-home mother. The family moved to Connecticut in 1994 when Dan Esty started the environmental law and policy program at Yale,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ct5thdistrict.registercitizen.com/elizabeth-esty/5/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022022746/http://ct5thdistrict.registercitizen.com/elizabeth-esty/5/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2013-10-22|title=Redlands Daily Facts Blogs|publisher=}}<!-- redirects to http://blogs.redlandsdailyfacts.com/, an empty blog site --></ref> before accepting appointment as Commissioner of the [[Connecticut Department of Energy and Environmental Protection]] from Governor [[Dannel P. Malloy]] in March 2011.<ref>{{cite web|author=Department of Environmental Protection |url=http://www.ct.gov/dep/cwp/view.asp?A=4013&Q=474242&depNav_GID=1511 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203071502/http://www.ct.gov/dep/cwp/view.asp?A=4013&Q=474242&depNav_GID=1511 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=February 3, 2012 |title=DEP: Governor Malloy Selects Daniel Esty to Head Newly Fused Department of Energy & Environmental Protection |publisher=Connecticut Department of Energy & Environmental Protection |date=February 10, 2011 |accessdate=June 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Women in the United States House of Representatives]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://esty.house.gov/ Congressman Elizabeth Esty] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.elizabethesty.com/ Elizabeth Esty for Congress] \n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Connecticut/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Elizabeth_Esty_%5BD-5%5D}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = E000293 | votesmart = 72826 | fec = H2CT05131 | congress = elizabeth-esty/2114 }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=Connecticut\n| district=5\n| before=[[Chris Murphy]]\n| start=January 3, 2013\n}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]]<br>D-[[Maryland]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=262nd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lois Frankel]]<br>D-[[Florida]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{CT-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Esty, Elizabeth}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Connecticut House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Female members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Connecticut Democrats]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from West Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:People from Oak Park, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Women state legislators in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]"}]}}}}